description.text:
Balance your lawnmower blades using this simple tool. Additional parts required are two standard 608zz skateboard bearings, two #4 x 1/2" screws, two 12.5x5 mm rare earth magnets and a M8x80 hex cap bolt. There are multiple blade holders published with this thing. One fits John Deere (splined) mower blades, and the other is for blades with the standard 16 mm (5/8 inch) sized hole. The SketchUp file is included for making your own blade holder.

example magnets: http://www.kjmagnetics.com/proddetail.asp?prod=D84

HUB: Prepare two 608 bearings so that they spin as freely as possible. I remove the shields and wash the bearing in solvent to remove the original grease. The thick grease slows the bearing down. Press the two cleaned bearings into opposite ends of the hub. Lightly oil the bearings with a few drops of thin machine oil. The bearings should turn smoothly and with minimal effort.
HOLDER: (1) Press the two magnets into the blade holder such that the magnets are flush with the blade side. (2) Use the two #4 screws to attach the blade holder to the hub. The heads of the screws should be below the surface of the holder that touches the blade.
MOUNT: Use the M8 bolt to hold the assembly's rotation axis horizontal. I drilled a 7mm hole into a block of wood and then screwed the M8 bolt into the hole. Once mounted the assembly should spin freely.

The axis of rotation (the M8 bolt) should be horizontal. The blade is centered on the hub via the holder and the magnets securely hold the blade in place. Turn the blade until it is horizontal and release. The heavy side will fall down.

NOTES:
(1) sometimes you might find that the hole is not centered in the blade which means the blade could be heavy along the thin edge and not the long edge. In this case the best remedy is to recycle the blade.

(2) In our experience if this balancer doesn't show a heavy side (no rotation when released) then you will not notice any vibration in use.

(3) Make sure the blade is clean of rust and lawn material or else the balance could change during use.

Thanks to my brother who had the original idea for this thing!

UPDATE-- After balancing my blades recently I found that they ran so smooth that I didn't notice they had switched off until I completed another lap around the yard! But I'm not complaining! :-)

description.text:
CAUTION: Very thin airfoil (test version weighs just 0.42 grams printed with 100% infill). If you want to print this, make sure your printer is properly calibrated, else risk the propeller breaking off if you plan on using it for more than testing purposes.

This propeller has been designed using the Onera HOR04 airfoil coordinates. All tests were performed on the Drone Propeller Thrust Testing Jig (all results below).

I printed this part with a slow setting, with the help of a 0.2mm nozzle at 0.04 layer height. I deburred and cleaned the print with the help of an X-ACTO Knife

After this, I then got to finish the propeller using a 500 grit sandpaper.

Here are the readings for a few voltage presets (also visible in the pictures taken):

  • 1.5V => 8.43 grams
  • 2V => 19.04 grams
  • 2.5V => 27.71 grams
  • 3V => 36.41 grams

The files I included contain all pictures relevant to the test, along with 6 txt files that contain airfoil coordinates, the STL files and finally the SLDPRT files. Should you want to play with the propeller, you need to get a bunch of 8520 coreless motors.

Use the SLDPRT files, in case you desire to make your own changes to the propeller.

Notes: The airfoil plotted by using the matplotlib library in python.

description.text:
Okay, I can't believe I'm adding to the oversupply of fidget spinners; but I've made these for friends and they are very popular and I haven't seen any like them. So here they are.

Personally I like the straight version but everyone else prefers the look of the curved version. Also shown is a (blurry) photo of one with multiple balls per arm -- go nuts if you want.

These are designed to use 3/8 inch steel balls which are readily available on-line. They are apparently often sold as sling shot ammo. If there is a metric equivalent near 9.5mm that anybody wants, let me know and I can add a version for that.

These use the usual 608 bearings.

I recommend printing this in PETG or ABS (or polycarbonate). PLA works but breaks too easily when they are inevitably dropped.

The original design is available from Onshape at:
https://cad.onshape.com/documents/875db54227b46569bce5cf3b/w/a9bc86a3641cb628e7b220ea/e/7eb588195532bac4b3c91d07
There are a couple other designs included there which work but aren't as entertaining.

Use whichever spinner caps you prefer. Shown are my favorites:
www.thingiverse.com/thing:2204246 by scotty13

EDIT:
and my new favorite:
www.thingiverse.com/thing:2314895 by vlevit

EDIT 2:
Added a version for 8mm balls by request. Untested.

EDIT 3:
Added a version for 1/2 inch balls by request. VERY UNTESTED. I don't recommend you make this unless you already have the 1/2" balls and want to give it a shot.
UPDATE: Based on a make by McUsher, the hub on this one was too thin. Added "Revised' version with a thicker hub. I'm not deleting the old version until the new version is confirmed as working.
UPUPDATE: Based on cbsarka's make, the revised 1/2" version works. Old version deleted.

The bearing should press in as usual with these things.

Snap the steel balls in with your fingers by pressing them down at a point about 1cm from the end farthest from the center.

The channels need to be clear of any printing blemishes; so if they occur, remove them as best you can. Moving the ball back and forth by hand usually clears any remaining rough spots. If one of the balls still doesn't roll freely, stick a small piece of fine sandpaper in the channel, roll the ball over it then slide the paper+ball back and forth a few times. I've only needed to do that a couple times but it worked amazingly well.

I have been looking on here for a while now for a iphone 5 stand that would work with the Lifeproof case and never found one. So I Finally decided to Design one myself. This Stand/Dock works with iphones that use the newer Lightning connector: 5, 5C, 5S. Stand can also be used without the Lifeproof case installed.
I designed this Stand for easy on and off by allowing the connector block to pivot. The connector block also engages into the lifeproof case several mm's for added strength and less stress on the lightning connector.
The Base Stand currently requires support for the pivot cavity (I plan to do a support free version soon). The base and Cable block can be difficult to snap together. The Cable block may also need some sanding to allow engagement of the Lifeproof case. Be careful when installing your cable so you dont damage it.
Enjoy
Update:
Added Stand Bases with built in support for the Pivot cavity. One with rear logo indent and one without logo. I recommend you use one of these base files instead of the older non supported ones, since cleanup will be much easier with these. Update:
Added different base configurations for the rear logo.
Added parts for Vibration issues. Printed with Flexible filament. E.G.: Ninja Flex
I noticed that the phone vibration would make an annoying noise against the back of the phone so i printed a flexible cap to add to the top to prevent this. Also added small feet to bottom for extra surface grip.
Next update will be support free.

Please use new Stand base's with support built in for the pivot cavity, It makes for an easier cleanup than if you generated support material.
Also print the cable block, install cable, then snap base and block together. It may be difficult to snap together.

title: Vertical Mount Immersion RC's FatShark FPV 600mw Transmitter with OpenSCAD Source

description.text:
After much experimentation on various types of mounts for the Immersion RC FatShark 600mw transmitters, I finally developed one that I liked enough to share. The goals were: 1) To get the clover leaf antenna as high above or underneath the airframe of the quad as reasonably possible. Antenna mounts in multiple orientations, up or down, etc..
2) Strong & light, but not too overly engineered.
3) TX LED visible
4) Provide plenty of cooling for TX
5) Flexible for varios multirotor or quadcopter airframes
6) OpenSCAD
7) Somewhat aerodynamic
8) Print with out supports (well I cheated somewhat on this, you can to print out the slip in TOOL to assist) This TX mount is designed to go onto aluminum 15.5mm HomeDepot towel rack bar that I use on my H quad, which can be found here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:190912. If you use a FatShark FPV TVL 600 CCD camera, you can use my http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:227037 to mount to the bar as well. NOTE: There are still a few little tweaks I want to make, so I might be updating in the future.

OPTIONAL - Make the TOOL first. 10% infill, .2mm layer height You can then use this TOOL as support for the opening of the mount. While you don't really need it, it just makes it much cleaner. For the mount, 20% infill, 2 shells, .2mm layer height Pause the mount print around 68%, insert the TOOL about 4cm or 1 inch into mount opening.
Continue the print. Once the print is complete, remove the support TOOL. Like I mentioned on description page, you don't really need to use the tool if you don't with, it still works fine on my Replicator 2, just have a few loose filament threads.

description.text:
This adapter was designed to attach a Pololu Universal Aluminum Mounting Hub (4-40 holes, 1/4" shaft) to a VEX 4" mecanum wheel without needing to make any permanent modifications to the VEX wheels. The adapter should be compatible with any of the other Pololu Universal Hubs that have the six mounting holes around the central shaft, but this has not been tested. 1-1/2" 4-40 machine screws (7x)
4-40 nylon locking nuts (7x)
5/8" 4-40 machine screws (6x) The holes are printed just slightly undersized, and are drilled out with a 1/8" drill bit to allow the screws to fit through the holes without engaging the threads. Original design work done in Lightwave, and was printed on a PolyPrinter Plus at the Dallas Makerspace.

title: Royal Game of Ur with Print-in-place hinged board

description.text:
Order one on kickstarter. https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/3dpprofessor/the-royal-game-of-ur-3d-printed-playable-replica

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_IE4RUTCkEE

Like Robert Ihnatisin, when I saw the British Museum's TableTop Day upload about the game of Ur, my mind immediately went to " I gotta 3D print that". But where I spent my time over-engineering it in my head, Robert just jumped in and made something. So thank you, Robert, for making this a much easier project for me, I was able to focus on another aspect of the game: making it shelf-able.

The changes from Robert's design include:

  • Pips on the dice
  • Better (IMHO) pawns
  • A hinged board that prints all in one piece and has plenty of space inside for component storage
  • Scaled to print on a MP Select mini (100mm^3 build area) so it should print on just about any printer and can be scaled up successfully

The video mentioned that they were playing a simplified rules. So while searching for advanced the rules for the game, and trying to figure out if the different spaces has any meaning, I found a scan from the British Museum's rules that indicates for the advanced game that you need 5 tokens with values 1-5 (with birds that don't mean anything) and some sort of currency. So I further modified the game with pawns that have values on the bottom side of 1-5 and I threw in a diamond token for currency. These elements are optional, but will allow for extended play and there's plenty of room in the board for 40 or so diamond tokens.

You can buy a printed set on Etsy: https://www.etsy.com/listing/530295893/royal-game-of-ur-3d-printed-board-game
If you like my work I hope you'll support me on Pateron: https://www.patreon.com/3DPrintingProfessor

MP Select Mini

No

No

0.15

20

Notes:

No supports should be necessary, and in fact supports can ruin the board so turn them off. Simply print standing up as is and when printing is complete run a blade between the parts to clean out any stringies until it opens easily.

To get the best results on the diamonds, print with transparent or natural filament, 1 shell, 0 infill, and at half the normal speed.

After printing the dice and pawns can have their details filled in with nailpolish and cleaned off with acetone to bring out the details. The board can be taped and spraypainted then wiped off before it dries to add some depth as well.

once printed.

description.text:
Use on any 608 bearing Fidget Spinner!

This is a remix of Travo's Penny Adapter for Fidget Spinners (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2254960). Like Travo I hate the idea of wasting money on 3 extra bearings that are just used as weights - even cheap bulk bearings cost 15-20c each whereas these weights come in at approximately 2c of filament (and 4c of pennies)!

I didn't like the open look with exposed pennies (or the possibility of them flying out) so I modified their design to include a top and bottom layer. The design is intended to be paused at approximately 6.4mm so that you can insert 4 pennies (US or Canadian) then resume the print, sealing in the pennies and creating a very nice 10g weight at exactly 22x7mm (same as a 608 bearing), perfect for your favorite Fidget Spinner.

I've included the GCode file from my Maker Select Plus (same as the Duplicator i3 Plus) that includes the pause at the correct height.

The design was also inspired by Malcolm3DPrinting's Enclosed Penny Spinner : http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2303216

title: Small Lab Supply based on DPS5015

description.text:
After making a small bench/lab supply using the DP30V5A adjustable supply controller from Banggood.com, I decided to up my game and do one using the DPS5015, 50V 15A unit.

https://www.banggood.com/DP50V15A-DPS5015-Programmable-Supply-Power-Module-With-Integrated-Voltmeter-Ammeter-Color-Display-p-1072236.html?rmmds=search

This a great unit and it costs about $40. It does need an external power source, so I bought a 48V 400W supply from banggood as well, for about $32

https://www.banggood.com/AC-110V-220V-to-DC-48V-400W-8_3A-Single-Output-Switching-Power-Supply-Transformers-Driver-p-1092410.html?rmmds=myorder

You will also need:
Sermos/Anderson power pole connectors for input & output power.
Banana jacks for output connection.
Power switch
Fuse holder
4 #2x3/8" screws
4 1" 6-23 nylon screws and nuts
Some wire, etc..

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

3mm 2 extra shells

Infill:

30%

Assemble the case

Use thick CA glue to assemble the parts of the case.

Glue the front panel to the base first, then the top.

I found that I had to sand the bottom of the front panel a bit to get it to sit flush at the top.

Getting a smooth finish

I went for the same smooth finish I did on my previous power supply. I used Bondo auto body putty to fill in the gaps between the "noodles". (This works for PLA, but not with ABS.)

I did this two times and wet sanded after each applictaion had dried. First with 240 grit then 400 grit.

It's simple and it works great. After spray painting you can't tell it's 3D printed.

I used Krylon 2X spay paint.

After Bondo and sanding, but before painting. After painting Final assembly

First I I wired up the two left hand banana jacks with leads that went to crimp on terminal lugs, then mounted them into the case.

The right hand banana jack is for the earth ground and gets a wire to one of the Sermos connectors on the rear.

Then I made terminal lug leads for the Sermos/PowerPole connectors, and the switch and fuse holder. The Switch and fuse holder are then mounted to the case.

The switch I used had a 12V LED in it, so I measured the current at 12V and calculated the resistor I would need to drop the extra voltage from my input (48V-12V=36V) at that current. I added that resistor in series with the LED lead of the switch. (Under the green shrink wrap in the picture below)

To mount the Sermos/Anderson power pole connectors for the input and output
power use #2x3/8" screws to hold them in place and some thick CA.

Then I installed the power supply board, putting the display cable on it first. The board is held in by the 6-32 nylon bolts/nuts thru the case bottom. The tricky bit is getting the input and output power leads connected!

Then connect the switch and fuse in series between the positive input power lead and the supply board.

Connect the cables to the DPs5015 display unit thru the front opening. After that insert the unit into the front panel.

The final step is to use 6 #2x3/8 screws to hold the back panel on.

Ready to screw on the back panel

description.text:
This is a Drip Stand for the Print Plate on a WanHao D7 and similar printers...
It holds the Print plate at an angle (currently 20 or 30 degrees) over the Resin Vat so that excess Resin can drain off and back into the printer. This Stand can remain mounted to the printer while a print is in progress and the main printer cover is on the printer...It need not be removed and replaced with each print.

Currently there are two versions: a 30 degree angle and a 20 degree both work.
The 20 degree is on the main Horizontal support so to reduce island and support issues with the SLA printers...technically either can be printed on either type printer.

I print these just as the are shown and used however I think they could be done in other orientations with the right support. I do use support when printing with PLA as the long bridges tend to sag.

I use PLA with 15% infill and 5-6 permitters to make the stand stiff yet light.
SLA is printed solid for now...it is not quite as stiff as the PLA but good enough.

A customizer of Torus knot. It's based on the path_extrude module and shape_pentagramfunction of my library.

I used a pentagram shape here; however, the 2D shape can be any shape.

The code is easy if you use my library.

include <rotate_p.scad>;
include <polysections.scad>;
include <cross_sections.scad>;
include <shape_pentagram.scad>;
include <path_extrude.scad>;

p = 2;
q = 3;
phi_step = 0.0125;
star_radius = 0.5;

pts = [
    for(phi = [0:phi_step:6.28318])
    let(
        degree = phi * 180 / 3.14159,
        r = cos(q * degree) + 2,
        x = r * cos(p * degree),
        y = r * sin(p * degree),
        z = -sin(q * degree)
    )
    [x, y, z]
];

shape_pentagram_pts = shape_pentagram(star_radius);

path_extrude(
    shape_pentagram_pts, 
    concat(pts, [pts[0]]),
    closed = true
);

There is quite a dearth of printable things from the Stormlight Archives by Brandon Sanderson that I intend to rectify.

I use a brim to aid in bed adhesion and my extruder/bed temperatures are 205/70 C, respectively. I use slow speeds around 30-40 mm/s for print accuracy, as well as lots of fine tuning for my particular printer.

Design details

AutoDesk Inventor 2017 Student License
~1-2 hours design time

-Googled 'Ohm symbol'
-Lots of arcs to design the shape first
-SAVED my progress
-Trimmed any excess intersections of lines to make it one enclosed shape
-Extruded to make it a solid object, then clicked View > Center of Gravity
-Left CG selected, but then removed extrusion to finish editing the 2-D sketch
-Made a circle with center at the center of gravity point, and another circle a couple millimeters larger with same center
-Trimmed the excess intersecting lines one more time to make the final object shape
-Extruded to 7 mm deep (depth of a bearing)
-Exported to STL

If you have any troubles with open loops after trimming your intersecting lines, use the Sketch Doctor feature to find and fix the issues!
NGSS

Momentum / Center of Gravity of Irregular Objects This is intended to be a qualitative analysis of momentum and CG, because the manual calculations of momentum and CG are both fascinating and tedious. I was able to find the center of gravity of this spinner using AutoDesk Inventor software during the modeling process. Center of Gravity/Mass:
Once the spinner has been printed and set with a new skateboard bearing, students can spin the object and feel the balance despite its irregular shape. There should be little or no vibrations felt if it has been printed properly with 100% solid fill. This is a demonstration of center of mass/gravity (these terms refer to the same point in this experiment) present on the axis of rotation. Momentum:
Fidget spinners are a beautiful demonstration of momentum at work - what keeps an object spinning once it is spun? Newton's law statest that an object in motion tends to stay in motion until acted upon by an opposing force (in this case, friction and wind resistance). More momentum allows the spinner to overcome these opposing forces for longer. This is why the original fidget spinner and many popular spinners have metal weights such as bearings in each arm. More mass => more momentum.

Changing the Properties of a Shape to Observe Changes in CG/Momentum This activity can be done several ways depending on access to materials. Center of Gravity:
Try printing one fidget spinner at 100% infill and one at 20% infill. Since the printer prints half of the shape solid and half of it with holes, one side will be heavier than the other (as seen in the photo below - this is just how the printer decides to print this particular shape at lower infill). You will notice that the non-solid spinner is now off-balance and causes vibrations as it spins. Since one side is heavier, the center of gravity has now moved away from the axis of rotation. Momentum:
This is best observed by printing an Ohm spinner as well as a traditional fidget spinner with four bearings. Once both spinners are printed and set with bearings, spin each object with equal force and observe how long each one spins. Was there a difference in the time they each spun? If done properly, the heavier spinner will spin for longer.

Materials and resources needed: 3-D printer capable of printing PLA
PLA filament (at least 15 g)
Skateboard bearings (1 for the Ohm, 4 for the traditional style spinner)
Ohm spinner
Traditional spinner (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1871940)
A sheet of lined paper to write down observations

I bought a cheap 1610 engraver (the LinkSprite, but honestly, I think they are all the same). It had some wing nuts for clamps but it was hard to get things to hold still on the bed. Print 4 of these and use the wing nuts to secure to the bed.

Unlike some of these, there is no T track, because the T-head bolt comes in from underneath. There is also a washer and I couldn't decide if it should go on the top or bottom of the part.

You want this fairly strong so 25% infill minimum. Layer height is no big deal. No support needed.

Although the bases tighten down nicely into the bed the jaws do not grip well. You may have to experiment with putting some material on the jaws or printing with harder plastic than PLA. Also, the wide base is good for clearance of the wing nuts but bad for eating up bed space.

It is probably obvious, but you can rotate these 90 degrees as you secure then. So you can use one on each side of the workpiece.

These would probably work better if they were stops on one side and somehow spring loaded on the other.

I did the original in Tinkercad, but I went back and did it again in OpenSCAD so I could put it into customizer so you can adjust for your needs.
